{{distinguish|Eotile language}} {{Infobox language |name=Beti |altname=Yaunde–Fang |states=[[Cameroon]], [[Equatorial Guinea]], [[Gabon]] |speakers=2.8 million |date=1982–2013 |ref=<ref>Sum of figures in ''Ethnologue'' 18</ref> |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Bantoid languages|Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] ([[Guthrie classification of Bantu languages#Zone A|Zone A]]) |dia1=[[Bebele language|Bebele]] |dia2=[[Bebil language|Bebil]] |dia3=[[Bulu language|Bulu]] |dia4=[[Eton language|Eton]] |dia5=[[Ewondo language|Ewondo]] |dia6=[[Fang language|Fang]] |dia7=[[Mengisa language|Mengisa]] |iso3=btb |iso3comment=(code retired) |glotto=yaun1239 |glottorefname=Yaunde–Fang (A.70) }} '''Beti''' is a group of [[Bantu language]]s, spoken by the [[Beti-Pahuin]] peoples who inhabit the [[rain forest]] regions of [[Cameroon]], [[Republic of the Congo]], [[Equatorial Guinea]], [[Gabon]], and [[São Tomé and Príncipe]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id%3Dbtb |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911151604/http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=btb |archivedate=2011-09-11 |df= }}</ref> The varieties, which are largely [[mutually intelligible]] and variously considered dialects or closely related languages, are: :[[Ewondo language|Ewondo]] (Yaunde) :[[Fang language|Fang]] :[[Bulu language|Bulu]] :[[Eton language|Eton]] :[[Bebele language|Bebele]] :[[Bebil language|Bebil]] :[[Mengisa language|Mengisa]].
Beti had an ISO 639-3 code, but this was retired in 2010 because the varieties of Beti already had their own codes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/chg_detail.asp?id%3D2009-032 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=20 September 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016214510/http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/chg_detail.asp?id=2009-032 |archivedate=16 October 2012 |df= }}</ref>
There is a Beti-based pidgin called [[Ewondo Populaire]].
