{{Unreliable sources|date=September 2008}}
[[File:Caucasus-ethnic en.svg|thumb|250px|Trialeti Ossetians are shown as the extreme southern area of the Ossetian population.]]
[[File:Soviet caucasus1922.png|thumb|250px|Map of Georgia in 1922 with Ossetian ethnic groups shown]]

The '''Ossetians in Trialeti''' ({{lang-os|Триалеты Ирыстон}}) are a group of ethnic [[Ossetians]], settling the central [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] districts of [[Khashuri district, Georgia|Khashuri]] and [[Borjomi]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hEAK9vLEcjYC&hl=en The Forsaken People: Case Studies of the Internally Displaced] by Roberta Cohen, Francis Mading Deng. Brookings Institution Press, 1998. {{ISBN|0-8157-1513-7}}, {{ISBN|978-0-8157-1513-9}}, page 296. ''The May 1996 memoramdum (......). Some Ossetians and even some Georgians have returned to South Ossetia, and some Ossetians have also returned to cities elsewhere in Georgia, such as Borjomi an Tbilisi.''</ref> historically part of the [[Trialeti]] province. The Ossetians resettled there in the 19th century from the territory, which is now known as [[South Ossetia]]).<ref>[http://www.sakartvelo.com/Files/Conflicts/minorities.html]</ref>

In 1922, after the [[Georgian–Ossetian conflict (1918–1920)|conflict]] between the [[Democratic Republic of Georgia|Georgian]] government forces and [[Bolshevik]]-sympathizing Ossetian rebels, and the forcible [[Sovietization of Georgia]], the recently created [[South Ossetian Autonomous Oblast]] within the [[Georgian SSR]] claimed the villages, mainly settled by Ossetians in Trialeti as its [[exclave]] - to no avail, however.<ref>{{ru icon}}Tsutsiev, Artur (2007). Atlas etnopoliticheskoy istorii Kavkaza (1774-2004). Evropa. {{ISBN|978-5-9739-0123-3}}.</ref><ref>{{ru icon}} [http://leftbooks.narod.ru/maps/1921.html Map with claimed territories]</ref>

In 1989 there were 38,000 Ossetians in the region, living in 134 villages.{{dubious|date=September 2008}} They had been incorporated into the Georgian society with a high degree of intermarriages with Georgians. During the [[1991–1992 South Ossetia War]], the area was unaffected by armed confrontation, but many Ossetian families had to flee rising ethnic discord to South Ossetia and [[Russia]]'s [[North Ossetia–Alania]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}}

